To verify the detailed chemical composition of CDs, the bonding configuration, and the surface functional state of atoms in CDs, XPS was performed. However, in the deconvoluted high-resolution XPS spectra and the P2p spectrum (Fig. 3
                        ), three different peaks located at 132.2, 134.1, and 135.2 eV were identified to indicate the presence of P-C, P-C/P-N (J. Li et al., 2017), and P-O (Hou et al., 2017) binding states of phosphorous, respectively. Also, 286.1, 289.7, and 290.3 eV peaks can be attributed to C-O/C-N, O-CO bonding (Dehvari et al., 2019), and CO3
                        2− (Jin, Wang, Yan, Zhang, & Zhong, 2019), respectively. Moreover, a short scan of N1s (Fig. 3) shows three major peaks linked to the CC-N (399.4 eV), C-N (400.1 eV), and N-H/pyrollic N (401 eV) (Choi et al., 2017). Similarly, the O1s short scan after deconvolution (Fig. 3) assigned C−OH/C−O−C, N-O, and CO binding states of oxygen with peaks located at 537.0, 537.9, and 538.8 eV, respectively (Dehvari et al., 2019).

Log-linear and Weibull models were used to study inactivation kinetics, and the resulting survival curves are presented in Fig. 6
                        . The first model is a simple first-order inactivation model, the second model demonstrates the decline in the bacterial population as a cumulative distribution of CDs. Both models successfully identified and explained the inactivation kinetics of both pathogens in the presence of CDs and the obtained R2 under treatment conditions was ≥0.9, which signifies the accuracy of the modeling; in contrast, to select the best-fitted model for the designed conditions, the lowest root-mean-square error (RMSE) parameters and Chi-square (χ2) values were considered (Taiye Mustapha et al., 2020). In the Weibull model, the survival curves were convex (β > 1) for both pathogens at a 1 MIC concentration (Fig. 6), and the lowest RMSE and χ2 values with higher R2 values represented the Weibull model fit better than the first-order model. Also, the calculated data suggested that the Weibull model has a particularly better fit for the antimicrobial kinetics of S. Typhimurium (Table 1
                        ). In both models, S. Typhimurium had a lower D-value than L. monocytogenes.

The hydrogen donor behavior of surface functional groups and electron transfer to CDs cores can be attributed to antioxidant activity, which is an attractive feature of CDs (Amit Kumar, Kumari, et al., 2019; Q. Li et al., 2022). With the increase in CDs concentration, the scavenging performance of CDs on DPPH radicals has significantly increased from 28% (at 0.1 mg/mL) to 38% (at 0.2 mg/mL) and 63% (at 0.3 mg/mL), while ascorbic acid exhibited 89% (at 0.3 mg/mL) DPPH radical scavenging activity (

                           Table 2


                        ). In addition, CDs demonstrated ABTS radical scavenging activity (99% at 2 mg/mL) compared to that of BHT (98% at 2 mg/mL) (

                           Table 2

                        ). The synthesized CDs demonstrate potent antioxidant properties, attributed to the presence of carboxyl and hydroxyl groups, as well as their larger size. Larger CDs potentially possess more surface antioxidant functionalities, allowing for increased interaction with the environment (Rodríguez-Varillas et al., 2022). This suggested a strong antioxidant capacity associated with the size and functional groups of the synthesized CDs. A higher ABTS scavenging activity in comparison with the DPPH assay can be associated with the higher solubility of CDs in the ABTS working solution than in the ABTS solution. CDs at lower concentrations also exhibited high ABTS scavenging activity in a concentration dependent manner. In this respect, scavenging activities of 93% and 94% were achieved from CDs at 0.5 and 1 mg/mL concentrations, respectively. The strong antioxidant activity of the synthesized CDs could be linked to their N-doped state, as previous studies have shown that N-doping can enhance the ability of CDs to scavenge ROS, possibly due to the electronegativity contrast between nitrogen and carbon (Ezati, Rhim, Molaei, Priyadarshi, et al., 2022). Additionally, radicals (e.g., ABTS•+ and ROS) can react with the large surface functional groups of the synthesized CDs and exhibit a high scavenging activity.
